    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. Could you explain how the distinction between COX-1 and COX-2 affects the actual physiological outcome? Specifically, why does the inhibition of COX-1 lead to more side effects in the stomach compared to when only COX-2 is targeted?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "COX-1 and COX-2 are isoenzymes with different physiological roles, though both are involved in the production of prostaglandins. COX-1 is constitutively expressed in most tissues, helping to maintain 'homeostatic' prostaglandin levels such as those that protect the stomach lining by stimulating the production of the gastric mucosal protective prostaglandin E2 (PGE2). Therefore, inhibition of COX-1 by NSAIDs like ibuprofen can disrupt this protective effect, diminishing the production of these stomach lining-protective prostaglandins, which can lead to irritation, erosion, and an increased risk of ulcers, hemorrhage, and other gastric complications.\n\n\nOn the other hand, COX-2 is induced by inflammatory stimuli and contributes primarily to inflammation and pain by promoting the generation of prostaglandins that mediate these responses. By selectively inhibiting COX-2, these actions related to inflammation, pain, and fever are mitigated, leading to therapeutic benefits without affecting COX-1 and thus avoiding the detrimental effects seen in non-selective COX inhibition. Some NSAIDs are designed to preferentially inhibit COX-2 to provide anti-inflammatory benefits with reduced gastrointestinal side",
      "source": "target",
